00:00:07.516 --> 00:00:17.500 A:middle
[ Music ]

00:00:24.516 --> 00:00:26.696 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:00:27.196 --> 00:00:27.696 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:00:29.086 --> 00:00:30.796 A:middle
My name is Susumu Harada.

00:00:30.796 --> 00:00:32.756 A:middle
I'm an engineer on the
Accessibility Team.

00:00:33.146 --> 00:00:35.166 A:middle
And I'm here today with
my colleague Patti.

00:00:35.576 --> 00:00:39.216 A:middle
And we're really excited to
introduce to you a new tool

00:00:39.216 --> 00:00:43.206 A:middle
that will make it easier than
ever for you to find, diagnose

00:00:43.346 --> 00:00:45.906 A:middle
and fix accessibility
issues in your apps.

00:00:47.236 --> 00:00:49.296 A:middle
So, some of you may be
new to accessibility.

00:00:49.526 --> 00:00:51.426 A:middle
So let me quickly go
over what it means

00:00:51.426 --> 00:00:54.186 A:middle
to make your app accessible
and some of the issues

00:00:54.186 --> 00:00:56.616 A:middle
that you may encounter
as you develop your apps.

00:00:58.336 --> 00:01:01.176 A:middle
So, accessibility
is about making sure


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:58.336 --> 00:01:01.176 A:middle
So, accessibility
is about making sure

00:01:01.426 --> 00:01:05.446 A:middle
that everyone can enjoy
the products and services

00:01:05.446 --> 00:01:07.346 A:middle
and the great apps
that you all create,

00:01:07.596 --> 00:01:10.876 A:middle
regardless of their abilities.

00:01:10.876 --> 00:01:12.816 A:middle
Now, some users may
have difficulty

00:01:12.816 --> 00:01:16.076 A:middle
with their vision
or their hearing.

00:01:16.646 --> 00:01:21.326 A:middle
And some may experience
physical and motor challenges,

00:01:22.816 --> 00:01:24.586 A:middle
or cognitive and
learning difficulties.

00:01:25.166 --> 00:01:29.586 A:middle
So, to support this
wide diversity of users,

00:01:30.106 --> 00:01:32.886 A:middle
we at Apple have worked
hard to make a number

00:01:32.886 --> 00:01:34.056 A:middle
of assistive technologies

00:01:34.396 --> 00:01:38.056 A:middle
that help augment various users'
abilities, such as VoiceOver

00:01:38.086 --> 00:01:40.656 A:middle
for people with visual
impairments, or Switch control

00:01:40.656 --> 00:01:42.416 A:middle
for people with motor
difficulties.

00:01:42.746 --> 00:01:48.806 A:middle
And we also made sure that these
are available on all devices

00:01:48.806 --> 00:01:51.226 A:middle
across all of our
platforms, from macOS

00:01:51.226 --> 00:01:54.266 A:middle
and iOS to watchOS and tvOS.

00:01:54.926 --> 00:01:59.146 A:middle
And while these assistive
technologies are great,

00:01:59.146 --> 00:02:01.126 A:middle
enabling tools, the heart


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.146 --> 00:02:01.126 A:middle
enabling tools, the heart

00:02:01.126 --> 00:02:03.996 A:middle
of our users' experience are
the great apps that you create.

00:02:04.506 --> 00:02:08.936 A:middle
So to better get a sense
for how your apps interact

00:02:08.936 --> 00:02:11.576 A:middle
with our assistive technologies
and the kinds of issues

00:02:11.576 --> 00:02:14.576 A:middle
that you may run into, let's
take a look at a quick example.

00:02:15.836 --> 00:02:18.816 A:middle
So here I have a simple app that
I created called Math Learner.

00:02:19.236 --> 00:02:22.326 A:middle
And it just presents a user with
an equation at the top to solve

00:02:22.646 --> 00:02:24.396 A:middle
and four answer buttons
on the bottom.

00:02:24.956 --> 00:02:27.376 A:middle
And the user can tap
on an answer button

00:02:27.436 --> 00:02:29.936 A:middle
and you get a feedback whether
or not the answer is correct.

00:02:30.406 --> 00:02:31.746 A:middle
It's pretty straightforward.

00:02:31.936 --> 00:02:33.546 A:middle
And it looks like its
functioning properly.

00:02:34.176 --> 00:02:38.446 A:middle
But how might a user who is
blind use this application?

00:02:39.796 --> 00:02:44.266 A:middle
So, obviously without any
assistive technology they won't

00:02:44.266 --> 00:02:45.366 A:middle
be able to see the screen.

00:02:45.676 --> 00:02:47.076 A:middle
So, it's pretty useless.

00:02:47.776 --> 00:02:51.226 A:middle
But fortunately, they can
use our screen reader called

00:02:51.226 --> 00:02:53.736 A:middle
VoiceOver to have
the information

00:02:53.736 --> 00:02:55.226 A:middle
on the screen read out to them.

00:02:55.386 --> 00:02:58.336 A:middle
And they can use various
gestures to navigate around

00:02:58.336 --> 00:03:00.306 A:middle
and interact with different
controls on the screen.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:58.336 --> 00:03:00.306 A:middle
and interact with different
controls on the screen.

00:03:00.856 --> 00:03:02.676 A:middle
So, if this app is
fully accessible,

00:03:03.086 --> 00:03:05.706 A:middle
when the user touches on the
screen showing the equation,

00:03:06.336 --> 00:03:09.276 A:middle
VoiceOver will read
out: "5 plus 3 equals."

00:03:10.146 --> 00:03:14.606 A:middle
Great. So what does the
assistive technology

00:03:14.606 --> 00:03:16.956 A:middle
like VoiceOver need
from your app in order

00:03:16.956 --> 00:03:18.806 A:middle
to present the interface
in a meaningful way?

00:03:18.806 --> 00:03:21.366 A:middle
So, there are several key
pieces of information.

00:03:21.786 --> 00:03:24.476 A:middle
But first it needs to know

00:03:24.476 --> 00:03:27.396 A:middle
where all the important
elements are on the screen.

00:03:28.836 --> 00:03:31.646 A:middle
And for each of those elements
it needs to know their traits

00:03:31.646 --> 00:03:35.616 A:middle
or their types such as what is a
button, heading or static text.

00:03:36.106 --> 00:03:41.116 A:middle
And finally, it also needs
to know a descriptive label

00:03:41.366 --> 00:03:44.476 A:middle
that uniquely identifies that
element so it can be described

00:03:44.506 --> 00:03:46.006 A:middle
to the user in an
understandable way.

00:03:46.006 --> 00:03:51.916 A:middle
So with these key pieces
of information VoiceOver

00:03:51.916 --> 00:03:54.626 A:middle
and other assistive technologies
can present the interface

00:03:54.716 --> 00:03:57.586 A:middle
to the user in a
very usable manner.

00:03:57.586 --> 00:04:02.526 A:middle
And all the accessibility
information is provided


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:57.586 --> 00:04:02.526 A:middle
And all the accessibility
information is provided

00:04:02.526 --> 00:04:04.896 A:middle
by the app through
our accessibility API.

00:04:05.856 --> 00:04:07.596 A:middle
And we at Apple have
worked very hard

00:04:07.666 --> 00:04:10.946 A:middle
to build accessibility support
right into our UI frameworks

00:04:11.406 --> 00:04:14.866 A:middle
so that if you build your apps
using standard controls all

00:04:14.866 --> 00:04:17.305 A:middle
of this accessibility
information will be filled

00:04:17.305 --> 00:04:19.206 A:middle
in for you automatically
by the framer.

00:04:19.206 --> 00:04:22.416 A:middle
And you don't have
to do any extra work.

00:04:23.086 --> 00:04:25.596 A:middle
But of course, your apps
will ultimately contain

00:04:25.596 --> 00:04:26.416 A:middle
custom controls.

00:04:26.416 --> 00:04:28.836 A:middle
And when they do, you
may need to provide some

00:04:28.836 --> 00:04:30.736 A:middle
of this accessibility
information yourself.

00:04:31.856 --> 00:04:34.506 A:middle
And if you don't, you might end
up with an inaccessible app.

00:04:35.176 --> 00:04:38.986 A:middle
So let's see what the impact
of that might be like.

00:04:38.986 --> 00:04:41.146 A:middle
So, if I had implemented
that equation view

00:04:41.146 --> 00:04:45.136 A:middle
at the top using complete custom
drawing code like CA Layers

00:04:45.136 --> 00:04:48.566 A:middle
or OpenGL, so they don't have
any accessibility information

00:04:48.566 --> 00:04:49.186 A:middle
by default.

00:04:49.186 --> 00:04:51.666 A:middle
So unless I explicitly
provide them,

00:04:52.776 --> 00:04:55.336 A:middle
they might be completely
invisible to VoiceOver

00:04:55.336 --> 00:04:56.656 A:middle
and other assistive
technologies.

00:04:57.176 --> 00:05:00.136 A:middle
And with these four
buttons at the bottom,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:57.176 --> 00:05:00.136 A:middle
And with these four
buttons at the bottom,

00:05:00.446 --> 00:05:03.316 A:middle
if I used custom views
that act like buttons,

00:05:03.706 --> 00:05:06.046 A:middle
but forgot to indicate
their accessibility trait

00:05:06.196 --> 00:05:09.066 A:middle
as being a button,
then VoiceOver

00:05:09.066 --> 00:05:10.786 A:middle
and their users will
have no idea

00:05:10.786 --> 00:05:12.566 A:middle
that they can press on these.

00:05:14.036 --> 00:05:16.066 A:middle
And finally, for the
Help button here,

00:05:16.516 --> 00:05:18.876 A:middle
if I implemented it using
custom drawing code,

00:05:19.236 --> 00:05:23.616 A:middle
and forgot to supply the
accessibility to the label,

00:05:23.616 --> 00:05:26.126 A:middle
VoiceOver will have no idea
how to describe it to the user.

00:05:26.356 --> 00:05:28.866 A:middle
And the user will have no
idea what that button is for.

00:05:29.936 --> 00:05:32.916 A:middle
So you can see how if you're
missing some key accessibility

00:05:32.916 --> 00:05:36.016 A:middle
information the user
experience for someone relying

00:05:36.016 --> 00:05:40.946 A:middle
on assistive technology
could be pretty bad.

00:05:41.076 --> 00:05:42.966 A:middle
So obviously it's very important

00:05:42.966 --> 00:05:46.326 A:middle
to make sure your app is
fully accessible, to make sure

00:05:46.326 --> 00:05:48.216 A:middle
that it has a positive
user experience.

00:05:49.536 --> 00:05:51.206 A:middle
But there's also
another added benefit

00:05:51.206 --> 00:05:52.936 A:middle
to making sure your
app is accessible.

00:05:53.026 --> 00:05:55.646 A:middle
And that is a fully
accessible app --

00:05:56.216 --> 00:05:59.626 A:middle
with a fully accessible app you
can write automated UI tests

00:05:59.626 --> 00:06:02.966 A:middle
for it using Xcode's
UI Testing Support.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:59.626 --> 00:06:02.966 A:middle
for it using Xcode's
UI Testing Support.

00:06:03.836 --> 00:06:06.306 A:middle
And for more information on
how to do that, I encourage you

00:06:06.306 --> 00:06:08.676 A:middle
to check out UI Testing
With Xcode session

00:06:08.676 --> 00:06:10.706 A:middle
from last year's WWDC.

00:06:13.746 --> 00:06:15.506 A:middle
Great. So, how can you make sure

00:06:15.506 --> 00:06:17.576 A:middle
that your app is
providing all the necessary

00:06:17.576 --> 00:06:18.756 A:middle
accessibility information?

00:06:19.316 --> 00:06:22.556 A:middle
Well, one method that
we've been recommending is

00:06:22.636 --> 00:06:25.506 A:middle
to use the actual assistive
technologies like VoiceOver

00:06:25.506 --> 00:06:27.266 A:middle
and Switch control
with your apps.

00:06:27.816 --> 00:06:29.876 A:middle
Now, this is still
the ideal method,

00:06:30.176 --> 00:06:33.346 A:middle
since you can mirror the
actual user experience

00:06:33.436 --> 00:06:36.836 A:middle
and also catch usability
issues beyond whether or not

00:06:36.836 --> 00:06:37.966 A:middle
that something is accessible.

00:06:38.976 --> 00:06:41.766 A:middle
But it does require that
you be familiar with how

00:06:41.766 --> 00:06:42.876 A:middle
to use these technologies.

00:06:43.946 --> 00:06:46.376 A:middle
And especially if your app
supports multiple platforms,

00:06:47.006 --> 00:06:49.026 A:middle
you might find it quite
challenging to have

00:06:49.066 --> 00:06:51.796 A:middle
to repeatedly deploy your
app on a specific device,

00:06:52.296 --> 00:06:54.766 A:middle
run through it using each of
the assistive technologies

00:06:55.116 --> 00:06:57.706 A:middle
and repeat the process
across each of our platforms.

00:06:58.266 --> 00:07:02.936 A:middle
And all those platforms also
have a number accessibility


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:58.266 --> 00:07:02.936 A:middle
And all those platforms also
have a number accessibility

00:07:03.066 --> 00:07:04.956 A:middle
settings that the
user can configure

00:07:05.416 --> 00:07:07.646 A:middle
such the Dynamic Type font size.

00:07:08.106 --> 00:07:12.906 A:middle
And you as a developer might
find it a little tedious to have

00:07:12.966 --> 00:07:15.696 A:middle
to go and switch back and forth

00:07:15.736 --> 00:07:17.596 A:middle
between changing the
accessibility setting,

00:07:17.916 --> 00:07:21.626 A:middle
going back to your app,
verifying its effect on your app

00:07:21.626 --> 00:07:22.666 A:middle
and repeating the process.

00:07:24.086 --> 00:07:25.916 A:middle
So, we've heard all
your feedback.

00:07:26.186 --> 00:07:30.486 A:middle
And today we're very excited
to announce a new, an easier,

00:07:30.486 --> 00:07:32.006 A:middle
and more streamlined alternative

00:07:32.196 --> 00:07:35.846 A:middle
to auditing your apps using the
new Accessibility Inspector.

00:07:39.046 --> 00:07:40.956 A:middle
And in the new Accessibility
Inspector,

00:07:42.026 --> 00:07:43.816 A:middle
with just a single
press of a button,

00:07:44.356 --> 00:07:45.966 A:middle
it can automatically
audit your app

00:07:46.186 --> 00:07:47.666 A:middle
for common accessibility issues.

00:07:48.036 --> 00:07:49.066 A:middle
It's super easy.

00:07:49.196 --> 00:07:52.226 A:middle
And it even suggests to you
how to fix those issues.

00:07:52.816 --> 00:07:57.136 A:middle
And in the Interactive
Inspection mode you can really

00:07:57.136 --> 00:07:59.156 A:middle
easily, point at any
element on your app

00:07:59.156 --> 00:08:01.606 A:middle
and get very detailed
accessibility information


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:59.156 --> 00:08:01.606 A:middle
and get very detailed
accessibility information

00:08:01.606 --> 00:08:02.086 A:middle
about them.

00:08:02.686 --> 00:08:05.666 A:middle
And this works whether your
app is running on a simulator

00:08:05.666 --> 00:08:07.256 A:middle
or on a connected device.

00:08:07.826 --> 00:08:13.796 A:middle
And we also offer a live
preview feature for settings,

00:08:14.416 --> 00:08:15.926 A:middle
which lets you really easily go

00:08:15.926 --> 00:08:17.416 A:middle
and change an accessibility
setting

00:08:17.556 --> 00:08:19.876 A:middle
and immediately see
its effect on your app

00:08:20.176 --> 00:08:23.766 A:middle
without having to
leave your app.

00:08:24.026 --> 00:08:26.246 A:middle
And we're really
excited to announce

00:08:26.446 --> 00:08:30.166 A:middle
that this Accessibility
Inspector now supports all

00:08:30.166 --> 00:08:30.906 A:middle
of our platforms.

00:08:31.436 --> 00:08:35.416 A:middle
This means that with a single
Accessibility Inspector app

00:08:35.416 --> 00:08:39.506 A:middle
on your desktop you can audit
and inspect your apps running

00:08:39.506 --> 00:08:44.096 A:middle
on macOS and iOS,
watchOS and even tvOS.

00:08:44.476 --> 00:08:48.306 A:middle
And you can do this simply
by launching your app

00:08:48.306 --> 00:08:50.056 A:middle
on the simulator or on a device

00:08:50.556 --> 00:08:53.126 A:middle
and choosing the respective
target from the inspector.

00:08:53.626 --> 00:08:54.306 A:middle
It's that easy.

00:08:54.896 --> 00:09:01.246 A:middle
And we hope that with this
feature it'll make it easier


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:54.896 --> 00:09:01.246 A:middle
And we hope that with this
feature it'll make it easier

00:09:01.246 --> 00:09:03.826 A:middle
than ever for you to test
an audit for your accessibly

00:09:03.826 --> 00:09:05.126 A:middle
across all of our platforms.

00:09:05.656 --> 00:09:09.676 A:middle
So, to give you a demo of
all these exciting features

00:09:09.676 --> 00:09:11.076 A:middle
and the new accessibly
inspector,

00:09:11.646 --> 00:09:14.456 A:middle
I'd like to hand
it over to Patti.

00:09:15.516 --> 00:09:20.046 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:09:20.546 --> 00:09:22.276 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hi. I'm Patty Hoa.

00:09:22.276 --> 00:09:25.306 A:middle
And I'm super excited to
be the one to tell you all

00:09:25.306 --> 00:09:28.146 A:middle
about our new Accessibility
Inspector.

00:09:28.556 --> 00:09:30.666 A:middle
So, we've been working
really hard

00:09:30.666 --> 00:09:32.066 A:middle
to incorporate all
your feedback.

00:09:32.656 --> 00:09:37.856 A:middle
And so I can't wait to
show you what we have.

00:09:38.476 --> 00:09:42.516 A:middle
So, to note, Accessibility
Inspector is now part

00:09:42.516 --> 00:09:43.906 A:middle
of the developer package.

00:09:44.256 --> 00:09:46.686 A:middle
That means you can
simply go into Xcode

00:09:47.116 --> 00:09:50.306 A:middle
under the Open Developer
Tools section in the minibar

00:09:50.926 --> 00:09:53.076 A:middle
and launch the Accessibility
Inspector.

00:09:53.986 --> 00:09:57.726 A:middle
So here is a screenshot of
our new Accessibly Inspector.

00:09:57.726 --> 00:10:00.786 A:middle
I want to bring your attention
to the top section first.


WEBVTT
